'''Ollie Imogene''' "'''Jean'''" '''Shepard''' (November 21, 1933 – September 25, 2016), was an American [[Country music|country]] singer who was considered by many writers and authors to be one of the genre's first significant female artists. Her early successes during the 1950s decade were said to influence the future careers of [[Loretta Lynn]], [[Dolly Parton]] and [[Tammy Wynette]].

Shepard was born in Oklahoma but raised in California alongside her nine siblings. Having a musical upbringing, she formed an all-female country music band named The Melody Ranch Girls. During this period, she was heard by country artist [[Hank Thompson (musician)|Hank Thompson]], who helped her get her first recording contract at age 18 with [[Capitol Records]]. Her second single with [[Ferlin Husky]] titled "[[A Dear John Letter]]" topped the country charts and reached the pop charts in 1953. In 1955, she had her first solo single top ten successes with "[[A Satisfied Mind]]", "[[I Thought of You]]" and "[[Beautiful Lies (Jean Shepard song)|Beautiful Lies]]". During this period she was among the first female performers to headline shows and consistently be played on country music radio.

In 1963, Shepard's husband [[Hawkshaw Hawkins]] was killed in a [[1963 Camden PA-24 crash|plane crash]]. Considering ending her career, Shepard ultimately returned and in 1964 had her first top ten single in nine years with "[[Second Fiddle (To an Old Guitar)]]". She had 15 more top 40 US country singles during the decade, including the top ten recordings "[[If Teardrops Were Silver]]", "[[I'll Take the Dog]]" and "[[Then He Touched Me]]". With a dip in commercial success, Shepard became frustrated with Capitol's lack of promotion to her material and moved to [[United Artists Records]]. In 1973, she had a comeback at age 40 with the top ten song "[[Slippin' Away (Jean Shepard song)|Slippin' Away]]". Four more of her singles reached the US country top 20 during the 1970s.

Shepard became part of the Association of Country Entertainers (ACE) in the 1970s, which advocated for traditional country music. Her criticism of the genre's [[Pop music|pop]] trends ultimately cost Shepard her recording contract from United Artists and she filed for [[bankruptcy]] during this time as well. Despite this, Shepard continued touring and became a popular attraction in European countries such as the UK and Germany. She continued sporadically recording as well, releasing her last studio album in 2000. Shepard also continued performing as a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]], whose cast she joined in 1955. In 2011, she was inducted into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] and continued performing through 2015.

==Early life==
Ollie Imogene Shepard was born in [[Pauls Valley, Oklahoma]] on November 21, 1933.<ref name="NY Times" /> She was one of ten children<ref name=washingtonpost>{{cite news|title=Country singer Jean Shepard dies; was Grand Ole Opry staple|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/country-singer-jean-shepard-dies-was-grand-ole-opry-staple/2016/09/25/4b1b907c-8349-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927112624/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/music/country-singer-jean-shepard-dies-was-grand-ole-opry-staple/2016/09/25/4b1b907c-8349-11e6-b57d-dd49277af02f_story.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 27, 2016|access-date=September 26, 2016|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=September 25, 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref> born to Hoit A. Shepard and Allie Mae Isaac Shepard. Both of her parents were [[Sharecropping|sharecroppers]]{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=25}} that raised cotton, sugarcane and peanuts.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=31}} Her father also worked additional jobs, including sewing burlap sacks at the Paul's Valley Alfalfa Mill.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=27}} When she was three, the family moved to [[Hugo, Oklahoma]] to be closer to her paternal grandparents. In Hugo, the Shepard family lived in a four-room house with little furniture{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=29}} while Hoit Shepard received a government loan to sharecrop with another farmer.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=31}} Along with many Oklahoma farmers during the [[Dust Bowl]], the Shepard family moved out west in search of a better life.<ref name="Rough Guide">{{cite book |last1=Wolff |first1=Kurt |title=Country Music: The Rough Guide |date=2000 |publisher=Rough Guides Ltd. |isbn=978-1858285344 |pages=195–196}}</ref> In 1943, the family settled in [[Visalia, California]].<ref name="Allmusic">{{cite web |last1=Cooper |first1=Dan |title=Jean Shepard Biography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/jean-shepard-mn0000189701 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=5 May 2024}}</ref>

In Visalia, Shepard skipped the third grade at Lynnwood Elementary School. In September 1947, she began the ninth grade at Visalia Union High School. In high school, she attended an accredited country music course and participated in the school's glee club.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=51}} She recalled being teased in her teen years for being an "Okie" who liked country music.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=52}} In tenth grade, Shepard and some friends formed an all-female country music band named the Melody Ranch Girls. Shepard played the [[Double bass|upright bass]] in the group.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=53-54}} Her parents pawned their home's furniture to buy the instrument for Shepard.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=158}} Along with playing the bass, Shepard also sang, claiming to have sung "90 percent" of the lead vocals in the group.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=55}} She then began playing alongside the Melody Ranch Girls every weekend during her high school years.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=158}}{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=54-55}} Shepard recalled being so tired after gigs that her teachers would let her sleep during school hours.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=55}} Shepard then graduated from Visalia Union High School at age 17 due to her previously skipping third grade.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=51}}

The Melody Ranch Girls continued performing following high school, finding gigs in northern California, Oregon and Washington state.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=158}} The group later split after many of the band members got married.<ref name="Ladies We Like">{{cite web |last1=Wolfe |first1=Allison |title=Ladies We Like: Jean Shepard |url=http://ladyfest.org/LadiesWeLike/Shepard_Jean.html |website=Lady Fest.org |date=November 20, 1998}}</ref> Prior to their disbandment, Shepard was heard singing in the group by country performer [[Hank Thompson (musician)|Hank Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Opry to celebrate 'grand lady' Jean Shepard |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2015/11/06/opry-celebrate-grand-lady-jean-shepard/74753096/ |access-date=5 May 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=November 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name="PBS">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Ken |title=Jean Shepard Biography |url=https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/country-music/jean-shepard-biography |website=[[PBS]] |access-date=5 May 2024}}</ref> Thompson was impressed Shepard and told her that he would secure her a recording contract.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=7}} It would be several more months before she heard back from Thompson.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=63}}

Hank Thompson brought an [[acetate disc|acetate]] recording of Shepard to [[Ken Nelson (American record producer)|Ken Nelson]] at [[Capitol Records]]. Female country artists were not yet in vogue, therefore Nelson was hesitant to sign her to a contract.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=7}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=158}} "There's just no place in country music for women. But every band needs a girl singer," Nelson told Thompson.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=7}}<ref name="Interview">{{cite web |title=Jean Shepard Interview |url=https://www.countrystarscentral.com/post/jean-shepard-interview |website=Country Stars Central |date=February 8, 2024 |access-date=18 May 2024}}</ref> Nelson then went to see Shepard perform live and was impressed. He succumb to offering her a contract, which had to be approved by a [[judge|court judge]] because she was only 18 years old. Because the judge did not have background in the music industry, he sent Shepard to find a music business professional to look over the contract. She then brought the contract to a radio executive who gave it his blessing. The contract was then approved{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=7-8}} and she officially signed with Capitol Records in 1952.<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web |last1=Cooper |first1=Daniel |title=Jean Shepard |url=https://www.countrymusichalloffame.org/hall-of-fame/jean-shepard |website=[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] |access-date=18 May 2024}}</ref><ref name="Rough Guide"/>

==Career==
===1952–1962: One of the first female country artists to find success===
On September 30, 1952, Shepard made her first Capitol recordings in [[Hollywood, California]].{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=9}} In February 1953, Capitol released her debut [[Single (music)|single]] "Crying Steel Guitar Waltz".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |last2=West |first2=Speedy |title="Crying Steel Guitar Waltz"/"Twice the Lovin' (In Half the Time)" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=February 1953 |id=F-2358}}</ref> The single was co-billed with [[steel guitar]] player [[Speedy West]] in belief that female country acts could not sell records alone.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=9}} The single was not a success.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> [[Ferlin Husky]] then approached Nelson with a song previously recorded and played in the California region called "[[A Dear John Letter]]".{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=10}} The song told the story of a [[Korean War]] soldier who receives a breakup letter from his female partner.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> In May 1953,{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=10}} "A Dear John Letter" was recorded with Shepard singing and Husky performing a spoken recitation.<ref name="Rough Guide"/> In July 1953, it was issued as a single and reached the number one spot on the US [[Hot Country Songs|country songs]] chart.<ref name="Country Songs">{{cite book |title= The Billboard Book Of Top 40 Country Hits: 1944-2006, Second edition|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |author-link=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=311}}</ref> It also [[Crossover music|crossed over]] to the number four position on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|pop chart]].<ref name="Pop Memories">{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories, 1890-1954 The History of American Popular Music: Compiled from America's Popular Music Charts 1890-1954 |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |isbn=978-0898200836}}</ref> The duo then cut a follow-up release "[[Forgive Me, John]]",<ref name="Allmusic"/> which reached the US country top five<ref name="Country Songs"/> and the US pop top 30.<ref name="Pop Memories"/> Through 1953, the Husky-Shepard duo toured the United States for a series of shows,<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=11}} making an estimated $300 per gig.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=11}} Because the legal age was 21 to cross state lines, Husky was appointed as Shepard's guardian.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=11}}<ref name="Hall of Fame"/>

[[File:Jean Shepard--1957.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A publicity photograph of Jean Shepard, circa 1957]]
In 1954, Capitol recorded Shepard twice more. This resulted in four singles, including "Two Whoops and a Holler" and "Please Don't Divorce Me".{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=28}} Husky and Shepard also disbanded their duet act the same year. She briefly located to [[Beaumont, Texas]] to work with manager Neva Starnes. Throughout the southwestern US, Starnes booked Shepard on road dates with up-and-coming performer [[George Jones]].{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} Around 1955, she joined the cast of the nationally-broadcast ''[[Ozark Jubilee]]'' television show.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}} On one broadcast, she performed a song she recently heard called "[[A Satisfied Mind]]". Ken Nelson was then informed of the performance and brought her to California to cut it one week later. In 1955, Capitol rush-released "A Satisfied Mind" as a single.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} Despite competing versions by [[Porter Wagoner]] and [[Red Foley]],{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} Shepard's version reached the number four position on the US country chart<ref name="Country Songs"/> and ultimately became her first solo commercial success.<ref name="Allmusic"/> Its follow-up "[[I Thought of You]]" reached the number ten spot in 1955. In addition, both of the singles' [[A-side and B-side|B-sides]] ("[[Take Possession]]" and "[[Beautiful Lies (Jean Shepard song)|Beautiful Lies]]") made the US country chart. Along with [[Kitty Wells]], her back-to-back hits made Shepard one of the first solo female country artists to make the US country top ten.<ref name="Country Songs"/>

Shepard's success led to her induction into the cast of the [[Grand Ole Opry]]. The induction took place on her birthday in November 1955{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} and she would remain a member for 60 consecutive years.<ref name="PBS"/> With her induction, Shepard was one of only four women in the cast: [[Minnie Pearl]], Kitty Wells and pianist [[Del Wood]].{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}} In addition, Shepard's commercial success made her one of the first solo female artists in country music to headline shows.<ref name="PBS"/> Shepard's fame prompted Capitol to issue her first studio album.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} In May 1956, ''[[Songs of a Love Affair]]'' was released.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Songs of a Love Affair'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=May 1956 |id=T-728 (LP)}}</ref> Considered one of the first country music [[concept album]]s,<ref name="Book 1">{{cite book |last1=Bruce |first1=Jennifer |last2=Lee |first2=Tena |title=Southern Music Icons |date=2022 |publisher=[[The History Press]] |isbn=978-1467145411 |page=31}}</ref><ref name="Hall of Fame"/> ''Songs of a Love Affair'' was a collection of songs that told the point of view of woman whose spouse has been cheating on her.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kienzle |first1=Rich |title=Southwest Shuffle |date=2013 |publisher=[[Taylor & Francis]] |isbn=978-1136718960 |page=213}}</ref> By this point, Shepard began working steadily at the Grand Ole Opry as the cast was expected to make 26 shows per year.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}} At the Opry, Shepard developed a romantic relationship with [[Hawkshaw Hawkins]] and the two later married.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}} The pair then started touring together{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}} with an ensemble that included horses and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] performers.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=100}}

Capitol also continued releasing new material by Shepard.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}} She stopped recording in California after realizing she was paying out of pocket for travel. Ken Nelson then began flying to [[Nashville, Tennessee]] to produce her beginning in 1957.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=92-93}} Despite a regular output of new single releases, Shepard was unable to have commercial success for several years. This was in-part due to the influx of [[rock and roll]] and the pop-influenced [[Nashville Sound]] that overshadowed Shepard's [[honky tonk]] sound.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}} One exception was 1958's "[[I Want to Go Where No One Knows Me]]", which made the top 20 of the US country chart.<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="Country Songs"/> In December 1958, Capitol issued her second studio LP ''[[Lonesome Love]]'', which was a concept album of love songs.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Lonesome Love'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=December 1958 |id=T-1126 (LP)}}</ref> Shepard continued playing road shows with Hawkins and the Opry into 1960. That year, she finished sessions on her third studio LP ''[[Got You on My Mind]]'', which Capitol issued in 1961.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}} Her fourth album ''[[Heartaches and Tears]]'' was released in 1962.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=20}} Critics noticed a slight incorporation of the Nashville Sound into these albums, along with Shepard's trademark honky tonk.<ref name="Rough Guide"/>{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=20}}<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Spotlight Winners of the Week |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 13, 1961 |page=28 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TCIEAAAAMBAJ&dq=this+is+jean+shepard++got+you+on+my+mind&pg=PA28 |access-date=5 May 2024}}</ref>

===1963–1972: Death of Hawkshaw Hawkins, comeback and leaving Capitol Records===
In 1963, Hawkshaw Hawkins was killed in a [[1963 Camden PA-24 crash|plane crash]], which also took the lives of [[Patsy Cline]], [[Cowboy Copas]] and the pilot Randy Hughes.<ref name="Tennessean">{{cite news |last1=Thanki |first1=Juli |title=Country Music Hall of Famer Jean Shepard dead at 82 |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/09/25/country-music-hall-famer-jean-shepard-dead-82/76568704/ |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=September 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Hall of Fame"/> Shepard was eight months pregnant and had a newborn child at the time of Hawkins' death.<ref name="Tennessean"/> After getting a settlement from the [[Piper Comanche]] company (whose airplane was involved in the crash), she debated ending her career.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=112}}{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} Ultimately, she resumed it after being persuaded by Opry president Jack DeWitt.<ref name="Tennessean"/>{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} Shepard then returned to the Opry stage several months after the crash.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=112-113}} She returned to the recording studio in August 1963. One of the songs recorded following the accident was "[[Two Little Boys (1964 song)|Two Little Boys]]".{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} The [[Marty Robbins]]-penned tune (written especially for Shepard) described how her children would carry on their father's legacy.<ref name="Two Little Boys">{{cite web |last1=Eder |first1=Bruce |title="Two Little Boys": Jean Shepard: Review |url=https://www.allmusic.com/song/two-little-boys-mt0012212260#review |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=26 May 2024}}</ref> "Two Little Boys" was the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] to her 1964 single "[[Second Fiddle (To an Old Guitar)]]".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}} The latter was considered her comeback recording<ref name="Two Little Boys"/> reaching number five on the US country songs chart, becoming her first charting single since 1959.<ref name="Country Songs"/> It was nominated for a [[Grammy Awards|Grammy award]] in 1965.<ref name="Grammys">{{cite web |title=Jean Shepard: Artist |url=https://www.grammy.com/artists/jean-shepard/6460 |website=[[Grammy Awards]] |access-date=27 May 2024}}</ref>
[[File:Jean Shepard--1966.jpg|thumb|left|180px|A publicity photograph of Jean Shepard, 1966]]

Now under the production of Marvin Hughes, Shepard's next studio album was 1964's ''[[Lighthearted and Blue]]''. The collection of cover tunes{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} was her first to make the US [[Top Country Albums]] chart, rising to the number 17 position.<ref name="Country Albums">{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn Presents Hot Country Albums, 1964-2007 |date=2008 |publisher=Record Research, Inc. |isbn=978-0898201734}}</ref> Following her comeback, Shepard had a series of US charting country songs, including 15 that reached the top 40.<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="Country Songs"/> In 1965, both "[[A Tear Dropped By]]" and "[[Someone's Gotta Cry]]" made top 40 appearances.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} Her 1966 single "[[Many Happy Hangovers to You]]", about a woman telling off an alcoholic husband, reached number 13 on the country chart. In 1966, both of her singles reached the country top ten: "[[If Teardrops Were Silver]]" and a duet with [[Ray Pillow]] called "[[I'll Take the Dog]]".<ref name="NY Times">{{cite news |last1=Grimes |first1=William |title=Jean Shepard, a Female Country Voice With Muscle and Ambition, Dies at 82 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/27/arts/music/jean-shepard-dead.html |access-date=5 May 2024 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 27, 2016 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 1967, both "[[Heart, We Did All That We Could]]" and "[[Your Forevers (Don't Last Very Long)]]" reached the top 20.<ref name="Country Songs"/> All seven singles were included on corresponding studio LPs that made the US country survey. Her highest-peaking LPs were ''[[Many Happy Hangovers]]'' (1966) and ''[[Heart, We Did All That We Could (album)|Heart, We Did All That We Could]]'' (1967), which both reached number six on the survey.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Critics from ''Billboard'' and ''[[Record World]]'' praised Shepard's vocal delivery and highlighted the emotional depth found in her albums of this era.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Album Reviews: Country Spotlight |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=March 11, 1967 |page=90 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CCkEAAAAMBAJ&dq=jean+shepard+heart+we+did+all+that+we+could+album+review&pg=PT1 |access-date=17 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |title=COUNTRY LP REVIEWS |magazine=[[Record World]] |date=November 9, 1968 |page=53 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Record-World-IDX/IDX/60s/68/RW-1968-11-09-OCR-Page-0053.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%20a%20real%20good%20woman%22 |access-date=19 June 2024}}</ref>

In 1968, Shepard wed musician Benny Birchfield{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}} and started working with new record producers.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=157-158}} This included Billy Graves (who recorded her 1968 LP ''[[Heart to Heart (Jean Shepard album)|Heart to Heart]]'')<ref name="Liner Notes">{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Heart to Heart'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=February 1968 |id=T-2871 (Mono); ST-2871 (Stereo)}}</ref> and Kelso Herston (who produced "Your Forevers Don't Last Very Long").<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title="Your Forevers (Don't Last Very Long)"/"Coming or Going" (7" vinyl single) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=April 1967 |id=5899}}</ref> Shepard disliked how Herston often came into scheduled sessions drinking and wanted a change in collaborators.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=158}} She then chose [[Larry Butler (producer)|Larry Butler]], a songwriter and aspiring record producer.<ref name="Kosser">{{cite book |last1=Kosser |first1=Michael |title=How Nashville Became Music City, U.S.A.: 50 Years of Music Row |date=2006 |publisher=[[Hal Leonard]] |isbn=978-0634098062 |page=181}}</ref> Butler met with Herston and was given permission to work with Shepard.<ref name="Billboard">{{cite magazine |title=UA Country Artists |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=October 9, 1976 |volume=88 |issue=41 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ySQEAAAAMBAJ&dq=jean+shepard+seven+lonely+days&pg=PT45 |access-date=28 June 2024}}</ref> Her first Butler-made recordings were released on the 1969 album ''[[Seven Lonely Days (album)|Seven Lonely Days]]''.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=158}}<ref name="Kosser"/> After two years of lower-charting singles, its [[Seven Lonely Days|title track]] reached number 18 on the US country chart in 1969.<ref name="Country Songs"/> It was followed by the number eight hit "[[Then He Touched Me]]", whose main character falls in love after giving up hope of finding it.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> The Grammy-nominated song<ref name="Grammys"/> was included on her 1970 album ''[[A Woman's Hand (album)|A Woman's Hand]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''A Woman's Hand'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=August 1970 |id=ST-559}}</ref> Her subsequent singles through 1971 made the US country top 30: "[[A Woman's Hand]]", "[[I Want You Free]]" and "[[With His Hand in Mine]]". The highest-climbing was the number 12 "[[Another Lonely Night (Jean Shepard song)|Another Lonely Night]]",<ref name="Country Songs"/> whose main character reluctantly chooses to stay with her partner.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> It was featured on her 1971 studio album ''[[Here & Now (Jean Shepard album)|Here & Now]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Here & Now'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=January 1971 |id=ST-738}}</ref>

In the early 1970s, Shepard became frustrated with the increasing lack of attention Capitol Records was giving to her music.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=157-158}}{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=24}} "I thought I was kinda lost in the shuffle," she later commented.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=157}} None of her Capitol singles following 1971 rose into the country top 40. Songs like "Safe in These Lovin' Arms of Mine" and "Virginia" only rose into the US country top 70.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Furthermore, her studio albums ''[[Just as Soon as I Get Over Loving You]]'' (1971)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''[[Just as Soon as I Get Over Loving You]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=August 1971 |id=ST-815}}</ref> and ''[[Just Like Walkin' in the Sunshine]]'' (1972)<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''[[Just Like Walkin' in the Sunshine]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Capitol Records]] |date=August 1972 |id=ST-11049}}</ref> failed to make the US country albums survey.<ref name="Country Albums"/> In 1972, Ken Nelson gave her a release from her Capitol recording contract.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=157-158}} "It was very hard for me. I cried like a baby," she remembered.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=24}}

===1973–1979: Second comeback in her forties, ACE and traditional country music advocacy===
In February 1973, Shepard signed with [[United Artists Records]]<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Williams |first1=Bill |title=Nashville Scene |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=February 17, 1973 |volume=85 |issue=7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QEUEAAAAMBAJ&dq=larry+butler+signed+jean+shepard+to+united+artists&pg=PT16 |access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref> and was given a large amount of money upfront to sign with the label.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=158}} Despite many Nashville executives believing she was past her prime,<ref name="Kosser"/> Shepard was encouraged by Larry Butler (who was now running the company's country music division) to sign with the label.<ref name="Kosser"/>{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=158}} Her first United Artists single was 1973's "[[Slippin' Away (Jean Shepard song)|Slippin' Away]]".{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=24}} Written by [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]],<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> "Slippin' Away" rose to number four on the US ''Billboard'' country chart,<ref name="Country Songs"/> number three on Canada's ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' country chart<ref name="RPM Country Songs">{{cite magazine|title=Search results for "Jean Shepard" under RPM Country Singles|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=4hgr7djetk7308bs87htaiiri6&q1=Jean+Shepard&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|magazine=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|accessdate=September 10, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024073559/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-110.01-e.php?PHPSESSID=4hgr7djetk7308bs87htaiiri6&q1=Jean+Shepard&q2=Country+Singles&interval=20|archive-date=October 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and made a brief appearance on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]].<ref name="Hot 100">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Top Pop Singles 1955–2010|publisher=Record Research, Inc|year=2011|pages=758|isbn=978-0-89820-188-8}}</ref> "Slippin' Away" became Shepard's highest-charting country single in nine years.<ref name="Country Songs"/> It appeared on an album of the [[Slippin' Away (album)|same name]] that went to number 15 on the US country albums survey.<ref name="Country Albums"/> The disc's second single "[[Come on Phone]]" reached the US and Canadian country top 40.<ref name="Country Songs"/><ref name="RPM Country Songs"/>

[[File:Jean Shepard--1976.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Jean Shepard, 1976]]
Shepard's restored commercial success at age 40 was due in-part to new production that featured upbeat tempos and hand-clapping background effects.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356}} Her music's lyrical content also shifted away from honky tonk themes towards subjects of devotion and romance.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/><ref name="I'll Do Anything It Takes">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''I'll Do Anything It Takes'': Jean Shepard: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/ill-do-anything-it-takes-mw0001892367 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref> Such themes were noticed in her follow-up studio album ''[[I'll Do Anything It Takes]]'' (1974). [[AllMusic]]'s Greg Adams compared Shepard's feminine themes favorably to that of similar songs by [[Tammy Wynette]].<ref name="I'll Do Anything It Takes"/> The disc reached number 21 on the US country survey.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Both of her singles from the album reached the US country top 20 in 1974: "[[I'll Do Anything It Takes (To Stay with You)]]" and "[[At the Time]]".<ref name="Country Songs"/> The latter was also penned by Bill Anderson, who also wrote her next two singles in 1975: "[[Poor Sweet Baby]]" and "[[The Tip of My Fingers]]".{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|p=356}} Both songs again reached the US country songs top 20<ref name="Country Songs"/> and Shepard dedicated her next studio album to Anderson<ref>{{cite book |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=Behind the Grand Ole Opry Curtain Tales of Romance and Tragedy |date=2008 |publisher=[[Hachette Book Group|Center Street]] |isbn=978-1599951843}}</ref> titled ''[[Poor Sweet Baby...And Ten More Bill Anderson Songs]]''. The disc featured the latter singles<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''[[Poor Sweet Baby...And Ten More Bill Anderson Songs]]'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[United Artists Records]] |date=January 1975 |id=UA-LA363-G}}</ref> and reached the top 50 of the US country chart.<ref name="Country Albums"/>

In 1974, Australian [[Pop music|pop]] singer [[Olivia Newton-John]] won the [[Country Music Association Award for Female Vocalist of the Year|Female Vocalist of the Year]] trophy on the televised [[Country Music Association Awards]]. In response, a group of country artists founded the Association of Country Entertainers (ACE), which advocated for the [[Country Music Association]] to promote the genre's traditional formats rather than appealing to [[Crossover music|crossover]] styles.<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite book |last1=Soelberg |first1=Paul J. |title=The Encyclopedia of Country Music |date=2012 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0199920839 |page=4}}</ref> Known in the industry for promoting traditional country music,<ref name="Rough Guide"/><ref name="Allmusic"/> Shepard was encouraged to join the cause{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}} and was named the group's president in the 1970s.<ref name="Rough Guide"/><ref name="NY Times"/> In her 2014 autobiography, Shepard claimed that she "wasn't ever president", but instead given all of the responsibility to run it.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=160}} According to the Encyclopedia of Country Music, the ACE failed to have "adequate funding" and ultimately disbanded as a result.<ref name="Encyclopedia"/> According to Shepard, the ACE disbanded because she loaned money from a bank to run a local office. Members failed to keep up with payments and she took [[Collateralized debt obligation|collateral]] on her home, but ultimately she filed for [[bankruptcy]], which led to the ACE ending.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=161-163}}

To regain footing following her bankruptcy,{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=163-164}} Shepard and Benny Birchfield bought a used [[Toyota]] and worked the touring circuit. Now her manager, Birchfield helped form her first full-time touring group named the Second Fiddles.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Country Artist of the Week: Jean Shepard |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=August 17, 1974 |page=38 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1974/CB-1974-08-17-OCR-Page-0038.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%22 |access-date=2 July 2024}}</ref> The Second Fiddles received equal billing on Shepard's 1975 live album ''On the Road''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=''On the Road'' (Liner Notes) [as Jean Shepard and the Second Fiddles] (Liner Notes) |journal=Jewel Records |date=1974 |id=LPS-407}}</ref> During this period, Shepard criticized crossover country on tour and at the Grand Ole Opry, which led to country music disc jockeys to stop playing her songs.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}} Singles like "I'm a Believer (In a Whole Lot of Lovin')" and "Mercy" only reached the US country top 50, while "I'm Giving You Denver" and "Hardly a Day Goes By" only reached the top 90.<ref name="Country Songs"/> Her final United Artists album was ''[[Mercy, Ain't Love Good]]'' which reached the US country top 40 in 1976.<ref name="Country Albums"/> Shepard claimed United Artists "could not keep the wheel rolling" and she attempted to work with a new producer, [[George Richey]].{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=168}} Despite the change, radio backlash and media publicity continued, resulting in United Artists dropping Shepard from their roster.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=164}}{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}} She then signed with the Scorpion label,<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Country: The Country Column |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=March 25, 1978 |page=56 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1978/CB-1978-03-25-OCR-Page-0056.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%20scorpion%20records%22 |access-date=2 July 2024}}</ref> who released her final-charting single "The Real Thing" in 1978.<ref name="Country Songs"/> She remained with Scorpion through 1979, signing a contract the same year with a new booking agency called Atlas Artist Bureau, Inc.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Country Column |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=January 6, 1979 |page=18 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/70s/1979/CB-1979-01-06-OCR-Page-0018.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%201979%22 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref>

===1980–2015: Continued touring, sporadic recordings and the Grand Ole Opry===
Finished with commercial country radio, Shepard continued touring and performing over the next several decades. Her music grew particularly popular in Europe, specifically in the United Kingdom where she performed frequently.<ref name="Allmusic"/> Among her first European engagements was the National Pure Country Music Tour in 1980 alongside [[Boxcar Willie]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Ball |first1=Angela |title=National Pure Country Music Tour In Lanarkshire, Scotland |magazine=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] |date=November 8, 1980 |page=26 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/80s/1980/CB-1980-11-08-OCR-Page-0026.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%201980%22 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> Other countries Shepard recalled playing included Ireland, Germany, Austria and Sweden.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=165}}

[[File:Jean Shepard (3469996106).jpg|thumb|left|170px|Shepard in mid-performance, 2007.]]
In 1981, Shepard was among several Grand Ole Opry members to record a studio album under the title ''[[Stars of the Grand Ole Opry (Jean Shepard album)|Stars of the Grand Ole Opry]]''. Released by the First Generation label, Shepard's album consisted of [[re-recording (music)|re-recordings]] and some new material.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Stars of the Grand Ole Opry'' (Liner Notes) |journal=First Generation Records |date=May 1981 |id=FGLP-GOOS-09}}</ref> ''Billboard'' critics found Shepard's performance on the album to be traditional compared to her earlier recordings.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Closeup |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 27, 1981 |page=80 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Billboard-Index/IDX/1981/1981-06-27-Billboard-Page-0096.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%20first%20generation%20records%22 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> In 1985, she collaborated with [[Roy Drusky]] on the studio album ''Together at Last''. Released on the Round Robin label, the project featured both duets and solo recordings by the pairing.<ref name="Together">{{cite journal |last1=Drusky |first1=Roy |last2=Shepard |first2=Jean |title=''Together at Last'' (Liner Notes) |journal=Round Robin Records |date=1985 |id=DTB-666}}</ref> During the second half of the 1980s, Shepard advocated for [[Vietnam veteran]]s{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}} by fundraising.<ref name="Music Row">{{cite magazine |last1=Oermann |first1=Robert K. |title=LifeNotes: Opry Matriarch Jean Shepard Passes At 82 |magazine=[[MusicRow]] |date=September 27, 2016 |url=https://musicrow.com/2016/09/breaking-opry-matriarch-jean-shepard-passes-at-82/ |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> Shepard often raised veteran's funds by playing shows, which sometimes were shut down by the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veteran's Administration]] because she did not receive permission to sponsor soldiers.<ref name="Ladies We Like"/> She continued advocating for traditional country music as well, criticizing [[James Brown]]'s 1988 Grand Ole Opry performance.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Thursday, March 10 |magazine=[[Radio & Records]] |date=February 26, 1988 |page=44 |url=https://www.worldradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-RandR-IDX/IDX/80s/88/RR-1988-02-26-OCR-Page-0044.pdf#search=%22jean%20shepard%201987%22 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref>

In 1991, the Country Harvest label released Shepard's second studio album of re-recordings titled ''Slippin' Away''.<ref name="Slippin Away">{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Slippin' Away'' |journal=Country Harvest Records |date=1991 |id=ER-111}}</ref> Labels began reissuing Shepard's 1950s Capitol material, beginning with 1995's ''Honky Tonk Heroine: Classic Capitol Recordings''. Released on [[compact disc]] by the [[Country Music Foundation]], the compilation also featured a biography and more details about the recordings in the liner notes.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Flippo |first1=Chet |title=Promoting Cleveland's 'Only Hillbilly', Reissues from Shepard, Hillmen |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=November 4, 1995 |page=55 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wg4EAAAAMBAJ&dq=jean+shepard+toured+in+europe+and+scotland&pg=PA55 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> Shepard also started appearing in filmed performances titled ''Country's Family Reunion'' during the 1990s.<ref name="Interview"/> Originally airing on the [[The Nashville Network|TNN]] network, the program eventually was released in a video format available for purchase.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Bessman |first1=Jim |title='Reunion' Success Reveals a Vital Country Market |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=June 6, 1998 |page=80 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bw4EAAAAMBAJ&dq=jean+shepard+country%27s+family+reunion&pg=PA80 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> In 2000, the [[Ernest Tubb Record Shop]] (which had its own distributing label) issued a new studio album by Shepard called ''The Tennessee Waltz''. The album featured covers, along with new material.<ref name="Tennessee Waltz">{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''The Tennessee Waltz'' (Liner Notes) |journal=[[Ernest Tubb Record Shop]] |date=2000 |id=ETRS-1020}}</ref> The Raney label then released Shepard's last album called ''Precious Memories'', a collection of [[Gospel music|gospel]] songs.<ref name="Precious Memories">{{cite journal |last1=Shepard |first1=Jean |title=''Precious Memories'' (Liner Notes) |journal=Raney Recording Studio |date=2000 |id=870-668-3222 (NO ID; recording studio original phone number)}}</ref>

Shepard also continued appearing as a member of the Grand Ole Opry.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> Along with [[Jan Howard]], [[Jeanne Pruett]] and [[Jeannie Seely]], she was named one of the "Grand Ladies of the Grand Ole Opry" for her dedication to the venue.<ref>{{cite web |title=10 Opry Women Who've Blazed the Trail |url=https://www.opry.com/story/10-opry-women-who-ve-blazed-the-trail |website=[[Grand Ole Opry]] |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> In 2005, Shepard celebrated 50 years as a member of the Opry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrymusic.about.com/od/cdreviewsmz/fr/CB_LCGrtLadies.htm|title=Great Ladies of the Opry/Grand Ole Opry Live Classics|website=Countrymusic.about.com|access-date=September 25, 2016|archive-date=January 20, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120101855/http://countrymusic.about.com/od/cdreviewsmz/fr/CB_LCGrtLadies.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> and, at the time of her death, she was the longest-running living member of the Opry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wixy.com/news/030030-oprys-oldest-member-is-now-ralph-stanley|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109053716/http://wixy.com/news/030030-oprys-oldest-member-is-now-ralph-stanley/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 9, 2015|title=Opry's oldest member is now Ralph Stanley|website=WIXY.com|date=March 11, 2011|access-date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> She also served as a spokesperson for the Springer Mountain Farms chicken company in the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Gayle |title=Jean Shepard Releases Autobiography |url=https://theboot.com/jean-shepard-autobiography/ |website=The Boot |date=June 11, 2014 |access-date=8 July 2024}}</ref> After 15 years of planning it, Shepard's autobiography was published in 2014 called ''Down Through the Years''. The book recounted the personal and professional memories of her life up to that point.<ref name="Down">{{Cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/6140784/jean-shepard-down-through-the-years-autobiography|title=Jean Shepard Reflects on Her Life 'Down Through The Years'|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> On November 21, 2015, Shepard became the first woman to be a member of the Grand Ole Opry for 60 consecutive years—a feat that only one other person had achieved at the time (founding member Herman Crook of the Crook Brothers), and only one other, [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]], has reached since.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musicrow.com/2023/07/bill-anderson-to-be-honored-as-longest-serving-grand-ole-opry-member/|title=Bill Anderson To Be Honored As Longest-Serving Grand Ole Opry Member|website=MusicRow.com|first=Lorie|last=Hollabaugh|date=July 6, 2023|accessdate=July 24, 2023}}</ref> She retired from the stage the same night.<ref name="Music Row"/><ref name=":0">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/grand-ole-opry-icon-jean-shepard-dead-at-82-w441864|title=Grand Ole Opry Icon Jean Shepard Dead at 82|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=September 29, 2016|archive-date=January 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129195530/https://www.rollingstone.com/country/news/grand-ole-opry-icon-jean-shepard-dead-at-82-w441864|url-status=dead}}</ref>

==Personal life==
===First marriage, annulment and second marriage to Hawkshaw Hawkins===
{{see also|1963 Camden PA-24 crash}}
[[File:Hawkshaw Hawkins--1957.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Shepard was married to fellow country artist [[Hawkshaw Hawkins]] who was killed in a plane crash in 1963]]
Shepard revealed in two sources that she was briefly married in 1951.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=56-58}}{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=6}} In her autobiography, she identified her husband's first name as Freddie but did not provide his last name. According to Shepard, the pair met after he was discharged from the [[United States Navy|Navy]].{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=56-58}} The pair met through Melody Ranch Girls member, Dixie Gardener. The pair then began going on dates and he soon proposed to her. Although she had second thoughts about the marriage, she wed Freddie shortly after her eighteenth birthday.{{sfn|Shepard|p=56}} According to Shepard, Freddie disliked the idea of his wife having her own career and attempted to end her first recording contract with Capitol Records.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=57}} "He wanted to get me back to Tennessee where he was from and keep me barefoot and pregnant," she told liner notes author Chris Skinker.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=6}} Shepard also stated that Freddie had a tendency to become violent and threatened her life on multiple occasions. After one altercation, Shepard moved out of the couple's California apartment and returned to her parents' home. Shortly afterward, Shepard and her mother went before a court judge who granted her an [[annulment]].{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=57-58}}

Shepard met her second husband [[Hawkshaw Hawkins]] at the ''Ozark Jubilee'' in 1955.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> After leaving the cast, she moved to Nashville, Tennessee where she ran into Hawkins again and the pair started a friendship.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=12}} The pair started a romantic relationship following Hawkins's divorce in 1958.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=97}} Inspired by [[Hank Williams]]'s wedding, Shepard and Hawkins wed on November 26, 1960 while onstage at a concert in [[Wichita, Kansas]].<ref name="Hall of Fame"/>{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=99}} In attendance was Ken Nelson (who gave Shepard away), Hawkins's secretary Lucille Coates and a local disc jockey broadcast the wedding over the radio.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=99}} Shepard gave birth to the couple's first child, Don Robin in 1961. He was named for the couple's friends, [[Don Gibson]] and [[Marty Robbins]].{{sfn|Skinker|p=22-23}} The couple toured together for the majority of their marriage,{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=98}} but when they were home they often spent time hunting and fishing.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=100}} Hawkins and Shepard lived on a three-acre home in [[Goodlettsville, Tennessee]] that included a horse stable.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=17}}

On March 5, 1963, Hawkins was traveling home to Nashville by airplane alongside Patsy Cline, Cowboys Copas and pilot Randy Hughes. At the time, Shepard was eight months pregnant with the couple's second child.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} That evening, while giving her son a bath, she began experiencing dizziness and sharp pain but ignored the symptoms and went to sleep. Shepard later theorized that her symptoms were associated with the timing of Hawkins's plane crash that day.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}}{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=108}} At 11:00 PM, she was awoken to a phone call from a friend who informed her that Hawkins's plane crashed. Shepard's doctor had to [[Sedation|sedate]] her so she could rest and a [[highway patrol]] officer was stationed at her home all evening. Several friends, including Minnie Pearl, stayed by Shepard's bedside that evening.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nassour |first1=Ellis |title=Honky Tonk Angel: The Intimate Story of Patsy Cline |date=1993 |publisher=St. Martin's Press |isbn=0-312-08870-1 |page=229}}</ref> At 6:00 AM, Hawkins's plane was found near [[Camden, Tennessee]].{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=109}} During her life, Shepard would criticize the way Patsy Cline's death in the crash overshadowed Hawkins's and others. "A lot of people think during this time that I've hated Patsy Cline, and that's not the story at all. I resented the way it was presented, like she was the only person on that airplane," she told ''[[The Tennessean]]'' in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cooper |first1=Peter |title=Patsy Cline: Country music remembers its darkest day |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/03/05/patsy-cline-country-music-remembers-its-darkest-day/81363382/ |access-date=10 July 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>

===Third marriage to Archie Summers, final marriage to Benny Birchfield and death===
[[File:Jean Shepard Hank Locklin and Don Robin--1966.jpg|thumb|left|220px|Jean Shepard with her son Don Robin, along with singer [[Hank Locklin]], 1966]]
Following Hawkins' death, Shepard's parents stayed with her to attend to domestic duties. She gave birth to Donald Frank Hawkins II one month after her husband's plane crashed in 1963.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=23}} "I was so devastated for a long time. A couple of years at least – it was just rough," she remembered about grieving Hawkins.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=110}} Shortly after his death, Shepard sold her husband's [[American quarter horse|quarter horses]]. After one was stolen off her property, she called the police and detective Archie Summers was sent to investigate the situation. Summers and Shepard began a romantic relationship shortly afterward{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=118-119}} and the pair married in 1966.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}} Shortly after marrying, she discovered that Summers was an [[alcoholism|alcoholic]] but tried to keep the marriage together so her children could have a father figure. When Summers appeared at one of her concerts drunk, Shepard decided to end their marriage.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=120}} In 1968, the couple divorced.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=159}}

Shepard's final marriage was to musician Benny Birchfield and they remained together until her death in 2016<ref name="NY Times"/> The pair first met at the 1966 Nashville Disc Jockey convention while Birchfield was playing in the [[Osborne Brothers]]' touring band. Birchfield then left the Osborne Brothers to play as Shepard's own road band. On the road, the pair developed a romantic relationship and the couple wed on November 21, 1968.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=137-138}} Shepard gave birth to the couple's only child together, Corey, on December 23, 1969. Birchfield also brought six more of his children into the marriage.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=142}} The couple eventually had 25 grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.<ref name="NY Times"/> The family lived for a time in [[Gallatin, Tennessee]] in a home that cost 250,00 dollars, according to Shepard.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=162}} Birchfield served as Shepard's manager following their marriage.<ref name="NY Times"/> During this period, Birchfield also worked as [[Roy Orbison]]'s bus driver and band member.<ref name="Tennessean 2">{{cite news |last1=Garrison |first1=Joey |title=UPDATE: 2 killed, husband of late country music star Jean Shepard injured in Hendersonville attack |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2016/12/17/2-killed-husband-late-country-music-star-jean-shepard-injured-hendersonville-stabbing/95560084/ |access-date=9 July 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=December 18, 2016}}</ref> Orbison often spent time at the couple's home in Nashville{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=144}} and he was visiting them several hours before his death in 1988.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Folkart |first1=Burt A. |title=From the Archives: Rock 'n' Roll's Roy Orbison Dies |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/archives/la-me-roy-orbison-19881208-story.html |access-date=9 July 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=December 8, 1988}}</ref>

In the 2010s, Shepard experienced trouble walking and had become immobile, relying on a wheelchair to move. After going to several doctors, it was discovered she had a brain deficiency and by 2013, it was treated and she resumed walking.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jean Shepard: Eddie Stubbs Celebrity Salute: WSM Radio |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8SueZDPkQoY |website=[[YouTube]] | date=November 4, 2014 |time=4:12 |access-date=10 July 2024}}</ref> She later was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] and became increasingly debilitated by the illness.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mirkin |first1=Gabe |title=Jean Shepard broke down barriers in country music, later battled Parkinson's Disease |url=https://www.villages-news.com/2016/12/18/jean-shepard-broke-barriers-country-music-later-battled-parkinsons-disease/ |access-date=10 July 2024 |work=Villages-News |date=December 18, 2016}}</ref> In September 2016, Shepard entered [[hospice]] care<ref name="Taste">{{cite web |last1=Reuter |first1=Annie |title=Jean Shepard's Funeral to Be Open to the Public |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/jean-shepard-funeral/ |website=[[Taste of Country]] |date=September 28, 2016 |access-date=9 July 2024}}</ref> and died on September 25 in Gallatin, Tennessee due from complications of Parkinson's and also [[Cardiovascular disease|heart disease]].<ref name="NY Times"/> She was 82 years old at the time of her death.<ref name="Tennessean"/> A public funeral was held in Hendersonville, Tennessee on September 29.<ref name="Taste"/> Following Shepard's death, Birchfield was stabbed at their home by the boyfriend of their granddaughter, Icey Sloan-Hawkins. Birchfield killed her boyfriend with a gun and Hawkins was also later pronounced dead.<ref>{{cite news |title=Report: Trying to protect granddaughter, country star's widower killed man, family says |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/jean-shepard-country-stars-widower-benny-birchfield-killed-man-after-granddaughters-stabbing-family-says/ |access-date=9 July 2024 |work=[[CBS News]] |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> An investigation found that Hawkins's boyfriend had stabbed her to death and that Birchfield acted in self-defense, dismissing him from being charged with crimes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cross |first1=Josh |title=No charges against Jean Shepard's husband in shooting |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/local/sumner/2016/12/20/no-charges-against-jean-shepards-husband-slayings/95672992/ |access-date=9 July 2024 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |date=December 20, 2016}}</ref>

==Artistry==
===Vocals===
[[File:Jean Shepard.jpg|thumb|right|170px|Shepard performing at a benefit event, 2006]]
Shepard's vocals have been described by music writers as having a raw and assertive sound that paired well with honky tonk music.<ref name="Allmusic"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}}<ref name="Rough Guide"/> Author Kurt Wolff described her singing style as being "hardcore" and further wrote, "She had a firm voice, one that could growl as well as yelp, yodel and cry."<ref name="Rough Guide"/> Edd Hurt of the ''[[Nashville Scene]]'' wrote, "Shepard stayed in control, but her voice gave body to songs that often explored the limits of what women could endure."<ref name="Nashville Scene">{{cite news |last1=Hurt |first1=Edd |title=Remembering Jean Shepard |url=https://www.nashvillescene.com/music/nashvillecream/remembering-jean-shepard/article_3f882505-c6f2-59e4-8941-73f1ba63f81a.html |access-date=11 July 2024 |work=[[Nashville Scene]]}}</ref> William Grimes of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that she had a "female country voice with muscle and ambition".<ref name="NY Times"/> Shepard also knew how to yodel, often doing so during live performances and occasionally on recordings.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=158-159}} Her yodeling was featured in the final section of her 1964 single "Second Fiddle (To an Old Guitar)"<ref name="NY Times"/> Shepard later credited [[Jimmie Rodgers|Jimmie Rogers]] records with teaching her how to yodel.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=5}}

===Musical styles===
Shepard was solely identified with the country genre throughout her career,<ref name="Allmusic"/> specifically with traditional country lyrically and musically.<ref name="Nashville Scene"/><ref name="NY Times"/> Her recordings were often categorized into the [[honky tonk]] sub-genre,<ref name="washingtonpost"/><ref name="Rough Guide"/> which pointed to themes of infidelity, alcohol, romance and relationships ending.<ref name="Hall of Fame"/>{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=143}} Critics referred to her Capitol recordings for displaying honky tonk themes and found them to be the most memorable by female artists. Dan Cooper of [[AllMusic]] wrote, "She cut one great record after another, mostly on Capitol Records. Nearly all of them crackle, no matter the topic, with honky tonk angel spirit."<ref name="Allmusic"/> Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann stated, "In the final roll call of the great female honky-tonk tunes are scores of Jean Shepard performances."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}}

Many of her 1950s and 1960s honky-tonk recordings portrayed women in assertive roles that predated the 1960s [[feminist movement]].<ref name="washingtonpost"/> William Grimes highlighted the songs "The Root of All Evil (Is a Man)" and "Many Happy Hangovers to You" for "planting the flag for independent women".<ref name="NY Times"/> Kurt Wolff named "Don't Fall in Love with a Married Man" and "Sad Singin' and Slow Ridin" to be "proto-feminist and downright bold".<ref name="Rough Guide"/> Author Peter La Chapelle wrote that she "not only sang pithy honky tonk numbers that bemoaned the behavior of the honky-tonk man, but even suggested that through collective action women could uproot the very foundations of the patriarchy".<ref>{{cite book |last1=La Chapelle |first1=Peter |title=A Boy Named Sue Gender and Country Music |date=2004 |publisher=[[University of Mississippi]] |isbn=978-1604739565 |page=38}}</ref>

Shepard's 1950s Capitol recordings were also part of the [[Bakersfield Sound]], a country sub-genre originating on the [[West Coast of the United States|American west coast]] that had a rawer sound than its Nashville counterpart and featured [[Fender (company)|Fender guitar]] instrumentation.<ref name="Music USA">{{cite book |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |last2=Hicks |first2=Samb |title=Music USA: The Rough Guide |date=1999 |publisher=Rough Guides Ltd. |isbn=978-1858284217 |page=406}}</ref><ref name="Bakersfield PBS">{{cite web |last1=Meares |first1=Hadley |title=The Streets of Bakersfield: Maverick Music in California's Nashville West |url=https://www.pbssocal.org/shows/country-music/streets-bakersfield-maverick-music-californias-nashville-west |website=[[PBS]] |date=September 13, 2019 |access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref> Her 1950s California recording sessions featured session musicians like [[Jimmy Bryant]], [[Roy Harte]], Fuzzy Owen, [[Buck Owens]], [[Cliffie Stone]], Lewis Talley and [[Speedy West]].{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=9-13}}<ref name="Panel">{{cite web |title=Women of West Coast Country: Panel Discussion |url=https://watch.countrymusichalloffame.org/videos/women-of-west-coast-country-panel-discussion |website=[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] |time=1:02:37|access-date=12 July 2024}}</ref> Many of these musicians later had careers of their own and worked alongside other west country performers such as [[Merle Haggard]].<ref name="Panel"/> Writers and historians considered 1953's "A Dear John Letter" to be the first commercially-successful recording to consist entirely of Bakersfield musicians.<ref name="Panel"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Jean Shepard: She gave Bakersfield Sound its first hit |url=https://www.bakersfield.com/special/year-in-review/2016/jean-shepard-she-gave-bakersfield-sound-its-first-hit/article_1d5dd897-6549-5f93-8e5a-d8901c48396e.html |website=Bakersfield.com |date=December 25, 2016 |access-date=12 July 2024 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

When the [[Nashville Sound]] musical style ushered in [[Pop music|pop]]-inspired trends, Shepard mostly kept her traditional sound,<ref name="Allmusic"/><ref name="Rough Guide"/> but at times experimented with softer pop elements.<ref name="Rough Guide"/> In reviewing 1958's ''Lonesome Love'', AllMusic's Richie Unterberger found that the album combined "good straight-ahead honky tonk" with "satisfying injections of pop"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Unterberger |first1=Richie |title=''Lonesome Love/This Is Jean Shepard'': Jean Shepard: Songs, reviews, credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lonesome-love-this-is-jean-shepard-mw0002154842 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=11 July 2024}}</ref> Chris Skinker of ''The Melody Ranch Girl'' box set noted that "the Nashville Sound was starting to creep into Jean's recordings" by 1961, specifically pointing to the "ethereal, echoey sound" of the guitar and the harmony vocals on specific songs.{{sfn|Skinker|1995|p=20}} As her career progressed, Shepard's song choices explored more contemporary themes of loyalty and faithfulness.<ref name="I'll Do Anything It Takes"/><ref name="Seven Lonely Days">{{cite web |last1=Adams |first1=Greg |title=''Seven Lonely Days'': Jean Shepard: Songs, reviews credits |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/seven-lonely-days-mw0001510662 |website=[[AllMusic]] |access-date=11 July 2024}}</ref> Other songs discussed sexuality such as 1974's "Poor Sweet Baby", which describes a woman and a man about to have intercourse. In 1975's "[[Another Neon Night]]", Shepard's character is involved in a one night stand.{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=356}}<ref name="Nashville Scene"/>

==Legacy, influence and achievements==
Music writers, historians and journalists have noted that Jean Shepard was among country music's first commercially-successful female artists.<ref name="Dictionary">{{cite book |last1=Abjorensen |first1=Norman |title=Historical Dictionary of Popular Music |date=2017 |publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]] |isbn=978-1538102152 |page=116}}</ref><ref name="Encyclopedia"/><ref name="Tennessean"/> With the exception of [[Kitty Wells]] and [[Minnie Pearl]], Shepard was considered one of the female singers in the genre to reach similar success.<ref name="NPR">{{cite news |last1=Farmer |first1=Blake |title='There Wasn't None Of Us': Jean Shepard, Country Music Trailblazer, Dies At 82 |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/09/27/495662800/there-wasnt-none-of-us-jean-shepard-country-music-trailblazer-dies-at-82 |access-date=13 July 2024 |work=[[NPR]] |date=September 27, 2016}}</ref> Peter Cooper of the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] wrote, "During the 1950s, few women managed to break through industry barriers to enjoy full-blown country careers, but Jean Shepard did just that."<ref name="Hall of Fame"/> [[Ken Burns]] of the [[PBS]] documentary ''[[Country Music (miniseries)|Country Music]]'' wrote, "In the 1950s, self-supporting female country artists were rare. Women who rose to stardom on the West Coast rather than through the Grand Ole Opry were rarer still, as were women who adopted a hard-edged honky-tonk style or sang from a woman’s perspective. Jean Shepard was all that and more."<ref name="PBS"/> Mary A. Bufwack and Robert K. Oermann further explained that she was an exception due to her being a single woman: "Jean Shepard's achievement is all the more remarkable because she was the only early-1950s country music woman who made it on her own."{{sfn|Bufwack|Oermann|2003|p=160}}

Shepard's success in the 1950s was said to have influenced the careers of future female artists in the 1960s like [[Loretta Lynn]], [[Tammy Wynette]] and [[Dolly Parton]].<ref name="Encyclopedia"/><ref name="Hall of Fame"/> Other female country singers have since considered Shepard an influence, including [[Elizabeth Cook]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Conway |first1=Tom |title=Elizabeth Cook fine with being country music outsider |url=https://www.southbendtribune.com/story/entertainment/music/2017/03/12/elizabeth-cook-fine-with-being-country-music-outsider/45803385/ |access-date=13 July 2024 |work=[[South Bend Tribune]] |date=March 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Reba McEntire]],<ref name="Taste 2">{{cite web |last1=Richards |first1=Kevin |title=Jean Shepard Discusses Hall of Fame Induction and Being a Pioneer for Women in Country Music |url=https://tasteofcountry.com/jean-shepard-country-music-hall-of-fame-interview-2011/ |website=[[Taste of Country]] |date=June 24, 2011 |access-date=13 July 2024}}</ref> [[Jeannie Seely]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Homer|first1=Sheree |title=Under the Influence of Classic Country |date=2019 |publisher=McFarland and Company |location=Jefferson, NC |isbn=978-1476637075|page=108}}</ref> and [[Connie Smith]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cooper |first1=Daniel |title=Connie Smith |url=https://www.countrymusichalloffame.org/hall-of-fame/connie-smith |website=[[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]] |access-date=13 July 2024}}</ref> Yet, Shepard was considered by writers not to get the credit she deserved. Bobbie Jean Sawyer of the ''Wide Open Country'' wrote, "Jean Shepard has never gotten her due recognition for opening doors for women in country music. But it's not too late to change that."<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sawyer |first1=Bobbie Jean |title=Female Country Singers: The Top 45 Singers of All Time |url=https://www.wideopencountry.com/female-country-singers/ |website=Wide Open Country |date=December 30, 2022 |access-date=13 July 2024}}</ref> Blake Farmer of ''[[NPR]]'' reported that many people believed her future membership into the Country Hall of Fame was "overdue".<ref name="NPR"/> In regards to her own legacy, Shepard believed for many years the Country Hall of Fame ignored her early efforts. "In my case, they were about 20 years overdue. I just at some point decided they'd forgotten about me, and I forgot about them," she wrote in her autobiography.{{sfn|Shepard|2014|p=203}}

In 2010, Shepard was inducted into the [[Oklahoma Music Hall of Fame]], her home state.<ref name="OK HOF">{{cite news |last1=Lang |first1=George |title=Oklahoma Music Hall of Fame inducts Jean Shepard, Les Gilliam, Sam Harris and Jamie Oldaker |url=https://www.oklahoman.com/story/entertainment/music/2010/11/05/oklahoma-music-hall-of-fame-inducts-jean-shepard-les-gilliam-sam-harris-and-jamie-oldaker/61202236007/ |access-date=13 July 2024 |work=[[The Oklahoman]] |date=November 5, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, Shepard was inducted into the [[Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum|Country Music Hall of Fame]] along with songwriter [[Bobby Braddock]] and fellow Oklahoma singer Reba McEntire.<ref name="halloffame">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-country-idUSTRE7205H820110301|title=Reba McEntire among Country Hall of Fame inductees|date=March 2011 |work=Reuters|access-date=March 1, 2011}}</ref>

